******
[1] Genome function analysis
Date: Thu 30 Oct 2014
Source: US News & World Report [summ., edited]
http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/10/30/enterovirus-may-have-caused-maryland-meningitis-outbreak


A meningitis outbreak at the University of Maryland may be related to another virus that has swept across the country [USA] during recent months, though further testing is being conducted to determine the possibility. If the tests are positive, it would mean that yet another manifestation of enterovirus-68 has occurred. In Maryland, the state public health lab is conducting a broad range of testing on specimens submitted to the agency, state epidemiologist Dr. David Blythe says. Agency officials would not specify whether testing for EV-68 was occurring and did not confirm whether samples had been sent to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC]. County health officials say that testing will occur at either the state level or be performed by the CDC.

Five viral meningitis cases at the University of Maryland were confirmed as having been caused by an enterovirus, according to the University Health Center, and it's possible the EV-68 strain is causing the outbreak at the school, where more than 20 students have been infected. So far, only one instance of the specific meningitis-enterovirus-68 match has been confirmed recently in the U.S. In Connecticut, an elementary school student tested positive Thursday [30 Oct 2014] for both viral meningitis and EV-68. EV-68 symptoms have varied widely during the recent outbreak, from severe respiratory illness to paralysis and muscle weakness -- even resulting in one death. Latest figures from the CDC show that 1101 cases have been diagnosed in 47 states and the District of Columbia. Almost all cases have been among children, and the virus strain seems to particularly affect those with asthma or a history of wheezing.

The University of Maryland's health center had issued a statement about the viral meningitis cases, not wanting to cause alarm and hoping to avoid public confusion about bacterial meningitis, a much more serious condition that can result in hearing loss, seizures, brain damage and death. Bacterial meningitis is treated with antibiotics, and most colleges require students to be vaccinated against it before they are allowed to attend. Viral meningitis, on the other hand, can be treated with bed rest and water, along with medication to relieve fever and headache.

Though a range of viruses can cause viral meningitis, it is possible that EV-68 is one of them, says Dr. Robert Wergin, president of the American Academy of Family Physicians and a practicing physician in Nebraska.

For reasons that remain unclear, University of Maryland officials say they will not know the particular strain of enterovirus behind the meningitis cases for weeks, according to an email from the University Health Center. Viral meningitis can come from a range of infections, including the mumps, herpes, measles, influenza, or even West Nile virus, though most cases are caused by an enterovirus -- cases of which are typically seen throughout the fall and spring. A teacher and a student also were infected with viral meningitis at a public school in the District of Columbia, only 10 miles away from the University of Maryland campus in College Park, Maryland. It is unclear whether a transmission occurred between the 2 or whether an enterovirus was the cause of the cases in the district. Other individual cases of viral meningitis have been confirmed across the country. Last week, an elementary school student was diagnosed with the virus [a virus?] in Stillwater, Oklahoma. Another case was diagnosed in a student at Sam Houston State University in Texas. Public information about what virus caused the meningitis or whether additional tests had been conducted was not released in either case.

Symptoms of viral meningitis can last up to 10 days and include fever, headache, nausea, vomiting, sensitivity to light and a lack of appetite. People generally recover spontaneously with supportive care, Wergin says. But as an enterovirus spreads, it can [may?] get into the tissues of the brain and spinal cord, causing inflammation. In rare, more severe cases, patients might require hospitalisation. It's unusual for an otherwise healthy person who is college-age to get viral meningitis, Wergin says; typically, it occurs among children younger than 5. It makes sense, however, that people could be more at risk in an enclosed environment like a classroom or dorm, he says.

[Byline: Kimberly Leonard]

