[2] Susceptibility analysis
Date: Thu 30 Oct 2014
From: Stephen J. Seligman <stephen_seligman@nymc.edu> [edited]


Comment on: Human enterovirus D68 - North America (14): genome sequence 20141029.2912217. Request for collaborators
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This ProMED-mail post reports on an investigation into sequence variation in the virus in an attempt to understand the epidemic potential and virulence of strains in the current outbreak. However, in addition to changes in the virus, rare human mutations affecting immunity to infection may be responsible for increased susceptibility to infections.

The laboratory of Dr. Jean-Laurent Casanova at Rockefeller University is devoted to the analysis of these kinds of mutations and has discovered numerous instances with increased susceptibility to a variety of organisms. They study cases and families in which unusual or unusually severe infections have occurred. Information thus far available (almost entirely from the news media) is limited. If confirmed by more complete investigation, the 3 fatal cases associated with enterovirus D68 in which the age and gender have been mentioned, fall into the category of unusually severe reactions to infection. One of these cases had concomitant _Staphylococcus aureus_ septicemia, a finding consistent with an immune defect that increased susceptibility both to the virus and to the bacterium. Dr. Casanova's laboratory would like to collaborate with groups that have access to specimens and families of patients who have died, with evidence of enterovirus D68 infection. CDC is aware of our efforts. Anyone with such access should contact me. All of the experimental work will be done in Casanova's laboratory.

An abstract outlining the general principles of the work follows. "Guidelines for genetic studies in single patients: lessons from primary immunodeficiencies" authored by Jean-Laurent Casanova, Mary Ellen Conley, Stephen J. Seligman, Laurent Abel, and Luigi D. Notarangelo, published in J Exp Med 2014 211:2137-2149. The Abstract states: "Can genetic and clinical findings made in a single patient be considered sufficient to establish a causal relationship between genotype and phenotype? We report that up to 49 of the 232 monogenic etiologies (21 percent) of human primary immunodeficiencies (PIDs) were initially reported in single patients. The ability to incriminate single-gene inborn errors in immunodeficient patients results from the relative ease in validating the disease-causing role of the genotype by in-depth mechanistic studies demonstrating the structural and functional consequences of the mutations using blood samples. The candidate genotype can be causally connected to a clinical phenotype using cellular (leukocytes) or molecular (plasma) substrates. The recent advent of next generation sequencing (NGS), with whole exome and whole genome sequencing, induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) technology, and gene editing technologies-including in particular the clustered regularly interspaced short palindromic repeats (CRISPR)/Cas9 technology-offer new and exciting possibilities for the genetic exploration of single patients not only in hematology and immunology but also in other fields. We propose 3 criteria for deciding if the clinical and experimental data suffice to establish a causal relationship based on only one case. The patient's candidate genotype must not occur in individuals without the clinical phenotype. Experimental studies must indicate that the genetic variant impairs, destroys, or alters the expression or function of the gene product (or 2 genetic variants for compound heterozygosity). The causal relationship between the candidate genotype and the clinical phenotype must be confirmed via a relevant cellular phenotype, or by default via a relevant animal phenotype. When supported by satisfaction of rigorous criteria, the report of single patient-based discovery of Mendelian disorders should be encouraged, as it can provide the 1st step in the understanding of a group of human diseases, thereby revealing crucial pathways underlying physiological and pathological processes."

--
Stephen J. Seligman, MD
Research Professor
Department of Microbiology and Immunology
New York Medical College
<stephen_seligman@nymc.edu>

[The 1st report advances the proposition that human enterovirus D68 virus infection may be the principal determinant of (non-bacterial) meningitis. While this is an interesting proposition, no conclusive evidence is presented to support this contention. The commentary from Stephen J. Seligman seeks collaborators in a different molecular approach to analysis of enterovirus D68 genome function. This methodology has not so far been employed in the analysis of human enterovirus D68 genome function. Thus at present there is no definitive evidence that enterovirus D68 infection plays a major role in viral meningitis. - Mod.CP]
